And it never went away.

summary: Good Omens Is a Delightful Apocalypse We'd Be So Lucky to Live Through
title: Good Omens Is a Delightful Apocalypse We'd Be So Lucky to Live Through
excerpt: The present-day pop cultural landscape in which Amazon’s adaptation of Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett’s Good Omens premieres is in a curious, apocalypse-obsessed state that Agnes Nutter would have found quaint, but fascinating all the same. Epic films and television shows about hapless heroes attempting to avert or prevent the prophesized end times are a dime a dozen, and audiences have become so inured to them that we don’t particularly care about the exact mechanics. The world is imperiled, heroes do what they can to save the day, things usually end up working out all right, and we’re on to the next doomsday blockbuster
description:
This book has meant so much to me since small times. It was one of the books that kept me the most company during the stagnant heat of the nineties in the Mid-South. I can’t explain how happy I am that the show not only looks good but, by all accounts, actually is.

The world seemed a great deal more worth saving back when this book was new, with a lot more future to it. I’m looking forward to seeing how the book’s essential dogged optimism translates to screen in this exhausted day and age.

summary: Aziraphale and Crowley dancing to soft, slow music played on an old gramophone late one evening after a couple drinks in the...
body:
Aziraphale and Crowley dancing to soft, slow music played on an old gramophone late one evening after a couple drinks in the little sitting room of their South Downs cottage, the lights low. Aziraphale’s head is resting gently on Crowley’s shoulder, his eyes closed as they sway in time with the music, and he’s just about to say it.

“My dear, I know I haven’t told you much, and I realize I probably should have said it long ago, but I really do–”

When suddenly “Get Thee Behind Me, Satan” by Ella Fitzgerald comes on. They don’t stop or change the song, but they do have a good laugh about it before sharing a awkward little chaste kiss on the lips.

“I know, angel. I know.”

summary: Help me find a post please?
body:
Help me find a post please?

There was a headcanon post going around a while ago that kind of went “what if Aziraphale’s name was originally ‘Aziraphael’, in keeping with how you spell&pronounce Raphael and other angel names of the kind, but because of its divine nature Crowley can’t say it and this is why he changed it around a little bit.”

I was so sure I reblogged it but now I can’t find it anywhere and I need it because of Reasons!

summary: Because I finally saw Detective Pikachu, some Pokemon headcannons: Crowley has an Ekans, Aziraphale a Starly. Aziraphale was...
caption:
Because I finally saw Detective Pikachu, some Pokemon headcannons:

Crowley has an Ekans, Aziraphale a Starly. Aziraphale was resistant to getting a Pokemon at all - books and animals don’t mix - but he found Starly with a broken wing, and upon healing it, the bird Pokemon wouldn’t leave him alone. Starly turns out to be quite good at fetching books for Aziraphale from the highest shelves, and is very careful with the pages, so their partnership works out quite nicely. Crowley, meanwhile, wanted a Pokemon from the get-go, and Ekans was an obvious choice. The snake Pokemon likes to drape itself around his shoulders (even when it starts getting too big for it). It also likes licking Aziraphale.
